english:
  title: Heavenly Envoy
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven blesses the Ming, granting it dominion over ten thousand lands. The four seas tremble at its majesty and bow to its virtue. Yet our Joseon has received the greatest share of this celestial grace, honored with an auspicious title and forever established as the Eastern Tributary. Now the Son of Heaven ascends the throne with ever-deepening regard for us, his gracious mandates descending in succession. Those who bear his commands are surely selected from the finest scholars of the court—the most talented and worthy.

    Thus in the third summer of Jianwen's reign, when the imperial edict came to invest our king, there arrived the Commissioner of the Bureau of Appointment, the Honorable Zhang Youchang, and the Court Calligrapher of the Wenxuan Pavilion, the Honorable Duanmu Xiaowen. Their prowess was vigorous and keen, their integrity clear and stern—rarely seen virtues that our people deeply admired. The following spring, the Calligrapher's younger brother, Xiaosu, promoted from Hanlin Historiographer to Vice Director of the Military Bureau, came in his brother's wake. His learning was penetrating and vast, his conduct incorruptible and conscientious—such that none could distinguish between the brothers' merit. In seal script, clerical script, and cursive forms, he had attained mastery beyond the mundane—a solitary pinnacle in this age that the whole realm could only marvel upon.

    Our king and all his people were moved by the Son of Heaven's virtue, stirred by the Calligrapher's purity, and delighted by the arrival of the Vice Director. They praised his brush-work as divine, and silken scrolls arrived daily seeking his calligraphy. During moments of respite from official duties, the Honorable One wielded his brush with miraculous swiftness, responding instantly to each request without the slightest weariness. Suppliants came in throngs, each departing satisfied. Thus our eastern people's respect and admiration for him deepened ever more.

    When the fifth moon arrived, the embassy's work completed, the envoy prepared his return journey. Our scholars of letters, acknowledging their humble offerings, each composed their thoughts as parting gifts. They entrusted me with composing this preface.

    I reflect that the Duanmu clan descends from Liyang, a preeminent disciple of the Sage himself. With brilliant and penetrating wisdom, Liyang sat directly before the Sage, participated in the discourse on language, and ultimately comprehended the principles of nature and heaven, ascending to sanctity second only to Yan Hui and Min Ziqian. Had he encountered imperial recognition and served in counsel, his achievements would surely have witnessed the great flourishing of the Way of Kings. Yet heaven did not bless Zhou, and he remained in obscurity, never fulfilling his destiny.

    Yet the grace of sages and worthies does not perish through ages, and the principles of all under heaven, long suppressed, must eventually unfold. Now these brothers—with their penetrating wisdom, their eloquent speech, their mastery of nature and heaven's way—have inherited and revived the thread of Liyang's teaching, dormant for millennia. They have encountered recognition from our Sagely Son of Heaven. Is this not heaven enriching Liyang's legacy, bringing forth capable worthies to serve the Luminous Empire, so that the Way, long obscured in former ages, might finally flourish in this day? Surely we shall witness the achievements of ministers rivaling those of the three ancient dynasties, their universal benevolence flowing forth to encompass the four seas, bringing our eastern realm into its blessed domain of supreme governance.

    Who would claim that the envoy's purity and abundant talent suffice as praise for such a one?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Jianwen (建文) refers to the reign period of the Yongle Emperor's nephew, during the early Ming dynasty.
  - key: ''
    value: Liyang (黎陽) refers to Duanmu Ci (端木賜), a renowned disciple of Confucius known for his ability to expound the Master's teachings.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three ancient dynasties' (三代) refers to the legendary Xia, Shang, and Zhou dynasties, representing the height of virtuous governance in classical Chinese thought.
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase 'Way of Kings' (王道) represents the ideal governance through virtue and benevolence rather than force, central to Confucian political philosophy.
